{
  "answer": "The verse work is **Cynewulf's *Elene*** (work slug: `cynewulf-elene-d2d132`), a single-chapter Old English poem whose closing passage (paragraphs [p-8f8a1b]–[p-dcbbfe]) matches the description exactly.[^1][^2]\n\nThe 'appled gold' mead-hall line reads: \"though in the mead-hall he received treasures, **appled gold**.\"[^3]\n\nThe three-tier eschatological fire-judgment passage reads:\n\n> Then into the fire’s grasp he will divide  \n> every person into three, of all who have ever been  \n> in this wide life over the broad earth.  \n> The righteous will be **uppermost in that fire**,  \n> the blessed company, a host eager for glory;  \n> they can endure it and without hardship  \n> easily bear it, that host of the brave.  \n> ...  \n> The sinful, mixed with malice, will be tormented  \n> **in the middle**, the heart-sorrowful men,  \n> in the hot surge, **covered with soot**.  \n> The third part, the accursed evil-doers,  \n> will be **in the fire’s depths**, the faithless traitors,  \n> fastened in flame for their former deeds,  \n> the godless host, in the grip of the embers.  \n> ...  \n> but they will be cast from that battle-heat  \n> **into hell’s abyss**, the bitter foes.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/).\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-8f8a1b).\n[^4]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-dcbbfe).",
